It wasn't a match made in heaven; it was more like a match made out of desire. I was drawn to her looks and her fearless attitude, while I led a conservative 9-to-5 lifestyle. She, on the other hand, took advantage of life and all it had to offer. If she felt like doing something, she did it without hesitation. I, on the other hand, took a measured approach to everything, always careful of how I appeared both in public and private settings.

I once met someone who I thought was my soulmate, but it wasn't Jada. She was cute, funny, and interesting. We would spend hours and hours together, shooting, eating, and talking about everything and nothing. I would call her every other day, and she was always there for me when I needed her. Even the Dekalb County police could attest to that. Although we went our separate ways, we always found a way back to each other. Looking back, maybe it was for the best that we never crossed that bridge. 
It's a question that people often ask: would you rather have a lover for a short time or a friend for a lifetime?

She is my sister, and I mean that in every sense of the word. We have a deep bond and know each other inside out. (We collectively know where the bodies are buried) It all started as a professional relationship, with her booking me to do an over-the-top Sweet Sixteen Shoot (you Know the MTV joints). But over time, we started talking and interacting more, and this led to a closer friendship. She's smart, funny, and always up for a good time. Every Thursday, Friday, and Saturday, it was all about "taking a shot," and "meeting at the Mexican" was always music to my ears (if you know Old NatL, you know what I mean). 

We even lived together for a while, and the stories we could tell are endless (but I won't). 

She's taught me a lot about integrity, and no matter what, we always did the right thing. Even when a promoter would mess with the money, and I wanted to go off on them, she would counsel me to stay calm and stick to our agreement. That's why doors are always open for her. 

She's one of my favorite people, and the sound of her voice always brings a smile to my face. The way she says my name is just the cherry on top. “Haaaay My Name”
People who are habitually Ducked up are Ducked up for a reason. Stop trying to save them. They are experts at being Ducked up, and they will put you in Ducked up situations and leave you there.

Most people assume that my friend is my wife, because we are so close. We have our own unique language and find joy in even the simplest things. Our daily business conversations are more of a formality than anything else, as we are really just checking in on each other's progress in taking over the world. I am envious of her freedom to do what she wants 99% of the time, while I am busy being the "smart guy" with a Ph.D. and making someone else rich. Our bond is so strong that it feels like we are more like twins than spouses.
